Myers Briggs personality prediction¶

Myers-Briggs Type Indicator (MBTI) is a personality test, typically based on psychological attributes and is used to determine differing strengths and types of personalities in a workplace or other setting. The questionnaire’s battery of tests can provide insight into the subject’s perception, decision making, leadership skills, and other attributes may contribute to personal or professional success.

The MBTI then segments subjects into 16 distinct personality types, using combinations of the following personality designations.

Introvert (I) vs. Extrovert (E) Introverts tend to consider the world from an internal perspective, allowing their ideas and creativity to flow from within themselves. Introverts tends to attach more emotional value to their thoughts and decisions.

Extroverts gain their inspiration through interactions and ideation with others. This external view tends to make extroverts more collaborative.

Intuitive (N) vs. Sensory (S) Intuitive types focus more on the future by recognizing patterns and processes in order to have a greater understanding of potential results.

Sensory types tend to live more in the moment and rely on holistic views through their use of immediate senses.

Thinking (T) vs. Feeling (F) Thinking types take an objective approach to situations, and rely more on causal analysis and data to help form their opinions or decisions.

Feeling types place considerable weight to external values as part of their decision making, giving more emphasis to the subjective aspects of a situation, and considering personal differences.

Perceiving (P) vs. Judging (J) Perceiving types go with the flow, and enjoy flexibility and spontaneity when it comes to agendas or decisions.

Judging types take an organized approach to life, and prefer that events be planned out or scheduled in order to go as smoothly as possible

There are 16 different personality types:

Project Idea¶

The Myers Briggs Type Indicator is a personality type system that divides a person into 16 distinct personalities based on introversion, intuition, thinking and perceiving capabilities. We can identify the personality of a person from the type of posts they put on social media.

I have downloaded the dataset from : https://www.kaggle.com/datasnaek/mbti-type. This dataset contains over 8600 rows. Each row has

  • Type
  • posts separated by '|||'

I have used NLP(Natural Language processing ) for this project .

Lets start out project by first cleaning the data .

lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

personality_test["cleaned_posts"] = personality_test["cleaned_posts"].apply(
    lambda x: " ".join(
        [
            lemmatizer.lemmatize(word)
            for word in x.split(" ")
            if word not in stopwords.words("english")
        ]
    )
)

Sentimental analysis¶

Sentiment Analysisis a procedure used to determine if a chunk of text is positive, negative or neutral. In text analytics, natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) techniques are combined to assign sentiment scores to the topics, categories or entities within a phrase

Perform sentimental Analysis scoring . Sentiment scoring takes very long nearly 15 mins to complete.

In [8]:
ana = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

sentiment_score = []

for post in personality["cleaned_posts"]:
    score = ana.polarity_scores(post)
    sentiment_score.append(score)

Segregate the individual sentiment scores as compound , positive , negative and neutral

In [9]:
personality["compound--sentiment"] = [score["compound"] for score in sentiment_score]
personality["positive--sentiment"] = [score["pos"] for score in sentiment_score]
personality["negative--sentiment"] = [score["neg"] for score in sentiment_score]
personality["neutral--sentiment"] = [score["neu"] for score in sentiment_score]

Sentiment scores will have negative values that Naive Bayes can't handle. So scale it using min max scaler.

In [10]:
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
personality["compound--sentiment"] = scaler.fit_transform(
    np.array(personality["compound--sentiment"]).reshape(-1, 1))
personality["positive--sentiment"] = scaler.fit_transform(
    np.array(personality["positive--sentiment"]).reshape(-1, 1))
personality["negative--sentiment"] = scaler.fit_transform(
    np.array(personality["negative--sentiment"]).reshape(-1, 1))
personality["neutral--sentiment"] = scaler.fit_transform(
    np.array(personality["neutral--sentiment"]).reshape(-1, 1))

We need to now count the number of words , number of unique words , number of colons , question marks ,exclamation marks , emojis , images etc . COUNTING: Methods used is as follows:

In [12]:
def words(s):
    w = set(s.split(" "))
    return len(w) / 50
In [13]:
def emojis(post):

    emcount = 0
    words = post.split()
    for e in words:
        if "http" not in e:
            if e.count(":") == 2:
                emcount += 1
    return emcount / 50
In [14]:
def colons(post):
   
    cocount = 0
    words = post.split()
    for e in words:
        if "http" not in e:
            cocount += e.count(":")
    return cocount / 50

Add new columns to our dataset for representings counts of images , emojis , question marks , exclamation marks , colons , words and unique words etc.

In [15]:
personality["question_mark"] = personality["posts"].apply(lambda a: a.count("?") / 50)
personality["exclamation_marks"] = personality["posts"].apply(lambda b: b.count("!") / 50)
personality["colon"] = personality["posts"].apply(colons)
personality["emoji"] = personality["posts"].apply(emojis)
In [16]:
personality["word"] = personality["posts"].apply(lambda c: (c.count(" ") + 1) / 50)
personality["unique_word"] = personality["posts"].apply(words)
In [17]:
personality["links"] = personality["posts"].apply(lambda d: d.count("http") / 50)
In [18]:
personality["images_count"] = [len(re.findall(r"(\.jpg)|(\.jpeg)|(\.gif)|(\.png)", post)) / 50 for post in personality["posts"]]

Distribution of personality types against number of posts.

In [34]:
dis = (
    personality.groupby("type")
    .agg({"type": "count"})
    .rename(columns={"type": "count"})
    .sort_values("count", ascending=False)
)
colors = {x: colors[x] for x in dis.index.tolist()}
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.title("Distribution of Personality Types", fontsize=30)
plt.ylabel("Number of posts", fontsize=20)
plt.bar(dis.index, dis["count"], color=list(colors.values()))
plt.show()

from sklearn.model_selection  import train_test_split

y=personality['Extrovert']
x=personality[['compound--sentiment','positive--sentiment','negative--sentiment','neutral--sentiment']]

Perform splitting.

In [37]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x,y,test_size=0.30,random_state=42)

Logistic model is used to model the probability of a certain event such as pass/fail , alive/dead etc . Import the Logistic Regression module.

In [38]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

Create a Logistic Regression classifier object and fit your model on the training set using fit() and perform prediction on the test set using predict()

In [39]:
